english:
  title: 'Three Offerings of Blue Words at the Hall of Manifest Correctness: A Prayer for Rain and Ritual to Avert the Calamity of Falling Stars and Perform the Great Unity Ceremony'
  author: Byeon Gye-ryang
  language: eng
  text: |-
    FIRST OFFERING

    Early autumn arrives, and we humbly raise this sacred altar.
    Though the rains have been scant,
    we pray that the celestial gaze will turn upon us.
    When devotion is sincere and unceasing,
    surely the Heavens will guide and uplift us.

    SECOND OFFERING

    The Way has no fixed form, its mysteries lie beyond our knowing.
    Yet when mortals offer true sincerity,
    the response comes swift as echo.
    Now we pour out our hearts in earnest supplication,
    once more approaching the Celestial Brightness.

    THIRD OFFERING

    That anomalies appear and disasters are shown
    is truly the merciful compassion of Heaven's heart.
    That calamity turns to fortune
    owes solely to the sustaining power of the Way.

    Thinking of my insignificance and humble nature,
    I have unworthily shouldered this heavy burden of state.
    From my ascent to the throne until this day,
    though dwelling in security, I have not forgotten peril.
    We looked to a modest prosperity, yet
    how has this ominous breath brought such disturbance?

    Falling stars lose their course—what ill omen this portends!
    Drought brings calamity—how can the people eat?
    The nation trembles in great fear,
    and the court officials raise their warnings.
    Can we seek blame elsewhere? No—
    we must look inward and accuse ourselves.

    Perhaps our reverence for Heaven and care for the people
    has not been sufficiently constant.
    Or perhaps our edicts and commands
    have not served them as they should.

    Moreover, among the many officials and countless people,
    in administering justice and determining cases,
    are there not wrongs left unredressed?
    In the heat of summer and the grip of winter,
    do not the aged and weak lose their shelter?

    All these failures stem from my insufficient virtue—
    justly does Heaven's reproach descend upon me.
    Yet what fault have the innocent multitudes committed?
    I can only grieve for the three harvests that yield no hope.

    I have ended feasting and music,
    yet my vigilance remains incomplete as distant thunder.
    I gaze at Heaven, I scan the clouds,
    but see only the harsh and brilliant sun.

    In deep reverence, we humbly beseech:
    Lend us your gracious favor and generous protection.
    Let the Book of Changes' regrets and sighs be forever ended.
    Bring joy and peace hereafter,
    that rain may fall abundant as in the Odes,
    soaking the earth with blessing.
    Let the harvest overflow with plenty,
    the nation overflow with riches,
    weapons be set aside, and peaceful times prevail.
  footnotes:
    - The 'Hall of Manifest Correctness' (昭格殿) was a sacred space for conducting state rituals and prayers to Heaven.
    - The 'Great Unity ceremony' (太一醮禮) was a major Daoist ritual performed for cosmic harmony and state welfare.
    - The 'Three Offerings' (三獻) structure reflects traditional Korean court ritual protocol with three stages of ceremonial presentation.
    - '''行潦'' refers to small pools of collected rainwater, used metaphorically here for meager precipitation.'
    - The reference to 'Book of Changes' (周易) and 'the Odes' (詩經) invokes classical Chinese literary traditions that influenced Korean royal discourse.
    - The 'three harvests' (三農) traditionally refers to grain crops, representing the agricultural foundation of the nation's welfare.
